aces exist\", destructures the void, spirals on the recovered error, and re-emits `organize_material`. NOT a missing runtime boundary — THING should TRUST the tasklist envelope, not re-inspect the filesystem.\n85\t- **Direction (human, after R14):** L1 in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`. After `await tasklist('organize_material', …)`, THING TRUSTS the returned envelope (`r.ok` / `r.data`), composes ONE closing reply from it, and ENDS the turn. Make explicit: do NOT verify the build by inspecting the project (no `inspect()`/`listProjectDir` \"to confirm tables/spaces exist\") — the tasklist already built and registered everything and its envelope is the source of truth; re-inspecting is both wrong (`inspect` returns void → the `[Symbol.iterator]` throw) and spirals into re-running the whole workflow. General principle: after a workflow tasklist returns its envelope, an orchestrator reports from the envelope and stops — it does not re-derive success by reading the filesystem. This is NOT L3 — do not add a runtime single-execution guard. After this, re-check `built:false`: it is most likely the second (racing) automator run and should clear once the workflow runs once; if it persists with a single run, trace the automator finalize separately.\n86\t- R15 · step 2 · L1 + L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer`, `organize_material/03-build_app` · verify=FAIL · L1 envelope-trust fix eliminated re-entry (one organizer), but direct automator still returned survey-only success with zero app artifacts; L2 app-architect action routed the build into the deterministic DAG yet its tasklist returned early before `create_project`/write nodes (no tables/pages). Next round: trace why the nested action tasklist has an immediate completed `build_app` child; do not undo organizer single-path or direct-delegate removal.\n87\t- R15 · step 2 · **L1 (envelope/no-self-inspect)** + rerouted 03-build_app → `app-architect#build_app` · verify=FAIL · **THE SELF-VERIFY FIX WORKED** — organizer now runs EXACTLY ONCE (both re-entries gone), and the partition is right (4 appropriately-scoped specialists). BUT the app still doesn't build: `appTables:{}`, `pageCount:0`, `built:false`.\n88\t- **ROOT of built:false (human, after R15 — WRONG PIPELINE):** R15 rerouted `03-build_app` to `system-appbuilder/app-architect#build_app`, but that is the **standalone-CATALOG** app pipeline (THING's path 4b — \"a NEW, shareable app UNRELATED to the current project's data\"); it builds a catalog template, not the current project, so it authored ZERO project tables/pages. The **LIVE-PROJECT** app is built by the **AUTOMATOR** (path 4a): `delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query })` — it holds `db:schema/db:write/pages:write/api:write/hooks:write` and `writeProjectTable`/`writePage`/`writeApi`, and republishes live. Earlier rounds' automator path DID create tables (cost_items, itinerary_legs, …) — it just didn't write PAGES / mark built (survey-only).\n89\t- **Direction (human, after R15):** in `organize_material/03-build_app.md`, REVERT the delegate target to the **automator** (path 4a, live-project), NOT `app-architect#build_app` (catalog). Keep the single-statement `currentTask.resolve(await delegate('system-appbuilder','automator', { query, attachmentIds }).then(app => ({ ok: app.ok===true, detail: … })))` shape. The query must ask the automator to build the FULL live-project app for the supplied material — tables AND the pages to view them — so the manifest ends with pages>0 and built:true (earlier automator runs made tables but pageCount:0). If the automator still stops at data-only, trace WHETHER the query asks for pages and whether `built` is set by a separate finalize the nested delegate skips. Everything else in step 2 is now correct (single run, right 4 specialists) — this is the LAST piece: a served app with real rows+pages.\n90\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"08b44427-7432-4e2d-a9c3-d9296f1761a5","uuid":"e6b3b034-ae07-44d0-ae64-d7e6141ef261","timestamp":"2026-07-16T04:17:20.393Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/attempts/06-tanzania.md","content":"# Attempt ledger — 06-tanzania\n\nCross-round memory for the judge. **Read this before attributing a failure**; **append one entry at\nthe end of every round.** One line per attempt. This is how a fresh-context round knows a rung is\nalready exhausted and it must CLIMB instead of re-trying the same rung.\n\nFormat per line:\n`R<round> · step <N> · <L0|L1|L2|L3> · <file#symbol> · verify=<PASS|FAIL|INTERRUPTED> · <evidence>`\n\n## step 1 — the dump (attachments → offer, nothing built)\n- R4 · step 1 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (no research during setup; complete per-part spaces; page-repair-is-write) · verify=PASS · committed\n- R5 · step 1 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (one final offer, not a progress placeholder; parallel Promise.all attachment reads) · verify=PASS · committed\n- R6 · step 1 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (delegate results are PLAIN TEXT, not objects) + prompt-contract.test.ts · verify=PASS · committed\n- R8 · step 1 · — · (no change) · verify=PASS · attachment flow stable across a fresh replay\n- R9 · step 1 · — · (no change) · verify=PASS · stable\n\n## step 2 — the bare \"yes\" → per-leg specialist spaces + DB + app, no research\nThe recurring hard one: THING builds FEWER specialists than the trip has legs, systematically\ndropping the MINOR legs (Cairo layover, Dar es Salaam transit) and keeping the salient ones\n(Serengeti/safari, Zanzibar), sometimes adding a generic catch-all.\n- R7 · step 2 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (itinerary/destination scope prose) · verify=INTERRUPTED · **OVERFIT to the travel domain** (human de-overfit it to a domain-neutral \"brevity is not a merge\" rule; anti-overfitting rule in judge.md/scenario-spec.md hardened to forbid domain framing, not just literal tokens)\n- R8 · step 2 · L1 · user-thing/thing/instruct.md (domain-neutral \"scope-inventory rule\": complete inventory of independently-owned scopes; brevity is not a merge; an overview supplements, never replaces) + org/docs/system-spaces/README.md · verify=FAIL (2 clean reruns) · both persona replays still dropped Cairo AND Dar; a direct-authoring probe built all four → primitive is NOT the gap\n- **Escalation note (human, after R8):** two L1 rounds of the RIGHT prose have not moved it, and the\n  SAME two legs drop every time → this is SYSTEMATIC, not variance, and NOT an L1 problem. The\n  granularity is decided by how many parts THING enumerates before delegating (the architect builds\n  one space per seed — `system-architect/.../01-design.md` designs ONE agent per call). A free-form\n  judgment that must come out the same every time wants a **DETERMINISTIC L2 structure**: an\n  enumerate-then-`forEach` tasklist that lists the legs as discrete items and builds one specialist\n  per item, so \"how many specialists\" stops being a per-run dice roll. Next round: CLIMB to L2; do\n  not write the instruction a fourth time.\n- R9 · step 2 · **L2** · NEW `user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/` (01-inventory → 02-build_specialist `forEach` → 03-build_app) + instruct.md delegates to it + `libs/core/src/spaces/system-spaces-dag.test.ts` + org/docs · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (ran out of context / runner timeout)** · **THE L2 FIX IS CORRECT AND WORKS FOR COVERAGE** — verify-rerun-3 built ALL FOUR legs (Cairo, Dar, safari, Zanzibar). It did NOT complete because the automator's app build then exceeded the runner's **10-min per-turn timeout**; the judge then hit \"Prompt is too long\" after 3 heavy reruns before writing a report. Inventory rule was iterated to its final form: READ the attached source docs before classifying scopes (earlier tries over-fragmented into facts, or missed legs).\n- **Direction (human, after R9):** DO NOT re-attribute and DO NOT rebuild `organize_material` — the L2\n  structure is right and already in the tree. The only reason step 2 didn't verify was the harness\n  per-turn timeout, now RAISED to 20 min (`sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/thing.mjs#dispatchAndWait`).\n  Round 10's job is narrow: rebuild, run ONE clean `--through 2` verify, confirm all four leg\n  specialists build ONCE each (no duplicate/overview catch-all) and the app builds, then judge step 2\n  PASS and continue to step 3+. Keep reruns to a MINIMUM (the build turn's trace is context-heavy —\n  don't burn context on repeats). If inventory still over/under-produces, tune ONLY 01-inventory's\n  rule; the structure stays.\n- R10 · step 2 · **L1 (architect action contract)** · `system-architect/agents/architect/instruct.md` (−12 net) + `libs/core/src/spaces/{prompt-contract,system-spaces-dag}.test.ts` · verify=**INCONCLUSIVE (ran out of context again)** · **DEEPER ROOT CAUSE found, past the L2 structure:** `organize_material`'s fan-out is WORKING — it enumerated all legs and fired all 5 architect delegates in parallel. But the architect's **action prompt manually CONTINUES after a tasklist result the runtime already auto-captures**; under the parallel `forEach`, that invalid cross-turn continuation clobbers sibling results → only the LAST architect build registers (some reruns instead over-produced 10 spaces w/ duplicate/overview junk — same bug, other face). R10 started the fix (delete the manual continuation, rely on the action runtime's envelope return) + updated both tests, but died of `Prompt is too long` before verifying.\n- **Context fix (human, after R10):** rounds 9 AND 10 both died of context exhaustion because\n  `step-NN.json` was an ~80KB full dump (every DB row + every yield's args) that the judge re-read\n  across reruns. FIXED: `run-yaml.mjs` now writes a ~10× smaller COMPACT `step-NN.json` (observables:\n  space names+count, table row-counts, delegate/yield kinds, errors, reply) and spills the raw dump to\n  `step-NN.full.json`; judge.md tells the jud