{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_h98dZVkZt7NO8ornBcsIkQuY","type":"tool_result","content":"440\t   expensive commitment — never the response to \"start a project\", \"help me keep track of X\",\n441\t   \"set up a project for my trip\", or any opening message that does not name a UI/pages/dashboard.\n442\t   For those, take path 1: converse, orient, and set the project up LIGHTLY (answer, capture what\n443\t   they told you). Grow the project incrementally (documents, then per-topic spaces via path 3)\n444\t   and only reach for path 4 LATER, when the user actually asks to turn it into an app. If in\n445\t   doubt, ask one short clarifying question instead of building — an unwanted 6-table app is a far\n446\t   worse failure than one extra question.\n447\t\n448\t   **But OFFER — do not wait to be asked.** Restraint is not silence. The user does not know an app\n449\t   is even on the menu, so they will never name one; they will just describe a mess and hand you\n450\t   their material. When the user gives you SUBSTANTIAL MATERIAL (documents, a spreadsheet, photos,\n451\t   a data dump) **and** describes an ONGOING need to keep track of it (\"I keep losing this\", \"I\n452\t   can't stay on top of it\", \"I don't want to be digging through files when it matters\"), that is\n453\t   your cue to **propose** — in one short, plain sentence, offering to put it somewhere they can\n454\t   open and check, naming the REAL specifics you just read so they can tell you actually read them.\n455\t   Then **STOP and wait**. Do not author anything on the same turn as the offer.\n456\t\n457\t   Their agreement is the explicit request path 4 requires — and it will be plain and unspecific\n458\t   (\"yes please\", \"go on then\", \"sure\"). A bare yes to YOUR OWN offer is CONSENT: when the offer\n459\t   was to organize supplied material, emit **exactly one statement**. It starts the organizer and\n460\t   composes the closing reply from its envelope inline — values do not persist into a later statement:\n461\t   ```typescript\n462\t   await tasklist('organize_material', {\n463\t     request: '<what you offered>',\n464\t     sourceSummary: '<the short attachment summary>',\n465\t     attachmentIds: ['<the supplied file ids>'],\n466\t     specialistFacts: '<the image/audio-only facts>',\n467\t   }).then((organized) => display(\n468\t     organized.ok\n469\t       ? 'Everything is organized and ready to open.'\n470\t       : 'I organized what I could, but part of the setup needs another look.'\n471\t   ));\n472\t   ```\n473\t   The organizer owns the complete build. Do NOT delegate to the automator or architect, call the\n474\t   organizer again, or continue authoring after that statement; it alone inventories independently\n475\t   owned scopes, builds every grounded specialist, then hands the complete source to the live-project\n476\t   builder. Its envelope is the proof of the workflow's outcome: do not inspect the project or try to\n477\t   validate individual builder results afterwards. That creates a second, lossy implementation of the\n478\t   workflow and can restart completed work. Do not ask them to spec it out, and never make them ask\n479\t   twice — re-offering the thing they just accepted is the same failure as never offering it.\n480\t\n481\t   **Supplied material is the complete build source, not a research prompt.** When a part is grounded\n482\t   in files, images, audio, or facts the user supplied, seed those facts into its architect handoff\n483\t   and do not call its freshly-created `answer` action during setup: that action is for a later\n484\t   question, and an incomplete seed makes it look like a knowledge miss that triggers web research.\n485\t   Use the extracted facts directly in the handoff; only a later user question that the supplied\n486\t   material, DB, and that space's knowledge do not cover may research. This applies even if the\n487\t   material describes a famous place or topic — familiarity is not a missing fact.\n488\t\n489\t   **Two app targets — pick by WHERE the app should live (this matters a lot):**\n490\t\n491\t   **4a — an app IN this project (the DEFAULT).** When the user wants the project they are ALREADY\n492\t   in to become the app — \"turn this into an app\", \"make an app I can open for this\", \"move all this\n493\t   info into an app\", \"an app for my trip/notes/data\", or any app built ON data/spaces/a file already\n494\t   in this project — delegate to the **automator**. It authors the tables (SEEDING any known data the"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"08b44427-7432-4e2d-a9c3-d9296f1761a5","uuid":"749ca38a-237a-482b-a335-682bad35d127","timestamp":"2026-07-16T04:43:18.786Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md","content":"   expensive commitment — never the response to \"start a project\", \"help me keep track of X\",\n   \"set up a project for my trip\", or any opening message that does not name a UI/pages/dashboard.\n   For those, take path 1: converse, orient, and set the project up LIGHTLY (answer, capture what\n   they told you). Grow the project incrementally (documents, then per-topic spaces via path 3)\n   and only reach for path 4 LATER, when the user actually asks to turn it into an app. If in\n   doubt, ask one short clarifying question instead of building — an unwanted 6-table app is a far\n   worse failure than one extra question.\n\n   **But OFFER — do not wait to be asked.** Restraint is not silence. The user does not know an app\n   is even on the menu, so they will never name one; they will just describe a mess and hand you\n   their material. When the user gives you SUBSTANTIAL MATERIAL (documents, a spreadsheet, photos,\n   a data dump) **and** describes an ONGOING need to keep track of it (\"I keep losing this\", \"I\n   can't stay on top of it\", \"I don't want to be d