RST — concrete):** all three nodes (`01-inventory`, `02-build_specialist`, `03-build_app`) say \"Emit these statements across turns\" and reference earlier-statement variables (`result`→`built`→resolve; `app`→`data`→resolve). **Variables DO NOT persist between statements** (each statement is its own module), so those cross-statement refs throw the \"unavailable `result`\" recovered-typecheck errors the report noted, and drive retries/instability (a likely contributor to the \"repeated organize_material + two automator delegates\" re-entry). REWRITE each node body to ONE self-contained statement that chains the delegate and `currentTask.resolve(...)` inline — exactly the \"one-statement action contract\" the architect node already uses. This is fixing the NODE code (L2), not the runtime (not L3). Then confirm the trace shows organize_material invoked ONCE and automator delegated exactly ONCE.\n76\t  2. **Inventory partition axis (the judgment core):** `01-inventory` keeps choosing CROSS-CUTTING facets (budget, logistics, travel-documents, a single photo/memo) as their own specialists instead of the user's real-world SEGMENTS. Make the partition axis explicit: one specialist per distinct real-world SEGMENT that owns its own body of facts (here: each place/stage of the trip); a cross-cutting facet (a budget, a documents checklist, one loose photo/memo, a travelers list) is APP DATA, never its own specialist. Domain-neutral, no leg/place literals. If this cannot be made reliable in prose because the partition is inherently model-judgment, DOCUMENT the missing primitive per the ladder before reaching for L3.\n77\t  Context death is fixed (compact evidence) and the routing is single-path, so a clean `--through 2` should now be judgeable: expect ONE specialist per segment, no cross-cutting-facet specialists, organizer runs once, app served with real rows.\n78\t- R13 · step 2 · L2 · `user-thing/tasklists/organize_material/{01-inventory,02-build_specialist,03-build_app}` · v