ry enumerated the RIGHT segments (Cairo, pre-safari, safari, Zanzibar, return). But attempt-3 still re-entered a SECOND time (2 organize_material runs, `built:false`). Judge hypothesized an L3 \"no single-execution boundary\" and stopped honestly.\n- **ROOT of the SECOND re-entry (human, after R14 — pinned from the trace, NOT L3):** it is THING SELF-VERIFYING the build after the tasklist. The exact recovered error: `Type 'void' must have a '[Symbol.iterator]()'` on the statement `const [dbEntries, spacesEntries] = await inspect([dbDir.entries, spacesDir.entries]);` — THING calls `inspect()` (returns void) to \"confirm tables and spaces exist\", destructures the void, spirals on the recovered error, and re-emits `organize_material`. NOT a missing runtime boundary — THING should TRUST the tasklist envelope, not re-inspect the filesystem.\n- **Direction (human, after R14):** L1 in `user-thing/agents/thing/instruct.md`. After `await tasklist('organize_material', …)`, THING TRUSTS the returned envelope (`r.ok` / `r.data`), composes ONE closing reply from it, and ENDS the turn. Make explicit: do NOT verify the build by inspecting the project (no `inspect()`/`listProjectDir` \"to confirm tables/spaces exist\") — the tasklist already built and registered everything and its envelope is the source of truth; re-inspecting is both wrong (`inspect` returns void → the `[Symbol.iterator]` throw) and spirals into re-running the whole workflow. General principle: after a workflow tasklist returns its envelope, an orchestrator reports from the envelope and stops — it does not re-derive success by reading the filesystem. This is NOT L3 — do not add a runtime single-execution guard. After this, re-check `built:false`: it is most likely the second (racing) automator run and should clear once the workflow runs once; if it persists with a single run, trace the automator finalize separately.\n- R15 · step 2 · L1 + L2 · `user-thing/thing#accepted-supplied-material-offer`, `organize_material